    "steps": [
      {
        "step_no": 1,
        "text": "Rinse rice until water runs clear; drain and cook rice using a rice cooker or on stovetop with a tight lid until tender. Fluff and keep covered.",
        "time_min": 25
      },
      {
        "step_no": 2,
        "text": "Prepare dashi: if using instant dashi, dissolve in hot water to make the specified volume; if making from scratch, simmer kombu and bonito flakes and strain. Keep hot. Brew sencha strong and combine with dashi if you prefer a tea-forward broth.",
        "time_min": 5
      },
      {
        "step_no": 3,
        "text": "Season the salmon lightly with salt and a little mirin. Heat a skillet over medium-high heat with a small amount of oil. Place salmon skin-side down and sear until skin is crisp, then flip and cook briefly until just cooked through. Remove and let rest; flake or slice into bite-sized pieces.",
        "time_min": 8
      },
      {
        "step_no": 4,
        "text": "Warm the dashi-green tea mixture, then add soy sauce and mirin; taste and adjust seasoning. Keep the broth hot but not boiling.",
        "time_min": 2
      },
      {
        "step_no": 5,
        "text": "Assemble bowls: divide steamed rice between bowls, place salmon pieces on top, and sprinkle sliced scallions, shredded nori, and toasted sesame seeds. Add umeboshi, wasabi, or pickled ginger if using.",
        "time_min": 3
      },
      {
        "step_no": 6,
        "text": "Ladle hot dashi-green tea broth over the rice and salmon to just cover or to desired level. Serve immediately while hot so the rice soaks up the broth.",
